# SECTION 1 — Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 What is VHDL?

**VHDL (VHSIC Hardware Description Language)** stands for **V**ery **H**igh **S**peed **I**ntegrated **C**ircuit **H**ardware **D**escription **L**anguage. It is a standardized, strongly-typed, hardware description language used to model, simulate, synthesize, and document digital systems at multiple levels of abstraction — from the algorithmic level down to the gate level.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Definition (Verbatim for Exam):**
> *“VHDL is a formal language used in the design and synthesis of digital systems, capable of supporting behavioral, dataflow, and structural descriptions of hardware.”*

It was originally developed under the **U.S. Department of Defense (DoD)** project in the **1980s** and was standardized by the **IEEE** as:
- **IEEE 1076-1987** (VHDL-87)
- **IEEE 1076-1993** (VHDL-93)
- **IEEE 1076-2008** (VHDL-2008) — most widely adopted by synthesis tools today.

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — The "Blueprint vs Recipe" Analogy

Imagine you are describing a dish to two very different chefs:

- A **Structural description** is like giving the chef a photo of the finished dish and saying *"lay ingredient A on top of ingredient B, side by side with ingredient C."* — You describe **how it's wired together**.
- A **Dataflow description** is like writing a **flow equation**: *"Final taste = 2 × sugar + 3 × spice."* — You describe the **flow of signals** from inputs to outputs.
- A **Behavioral description** is like saying *"cook until golden, stirring when needed."* — You describe the **function/algorithm** without caring about wiring.

VHDL lets you describe hardware in **all three styles** simultaneously or in isolation — a feature no schematic capture tool provides.

## 1.3 Why KTU Engineers Study VHDL (Syllabus Relevance)

> [!NOTE]
> In the **KTU 2024 Scheme (PEEET523)**, VHDL forms the **backbone** of Module 4 and is a **frequent question in Part B (14-mark)** and **lab viva** assessments. Mastery here directly maps to **CO4**: *“Design and simulate combinational and sequential digital circuits using HDL.”*

The **synthesis-driven subset** of VHDL — the subset accepted by synthesis tools (Xilinx Vivado, Intel Quartus, Synopsys Design Compiler) — is what students must master. Anything beyond this subset (e.g., file I/O, floating point in pure form) is **simulation-only** and generally **non-synthesizable**.

## 1.4 Fundamental VHDL Design Units — The "Three Pillars"

| Unit | Purpose | Analogy |
|------|---------|---------|
| **Entity** | Defines the **interface** (input/output ports) of a circuit | The **black box label** with pin names |
| **Architecture** | Defines the **function or structure** inside the entity | The **internal wiring** or recipe |
| **Configuration** | Binds an entity to a specific architecture during simulation | Choosing which **internal wiring diagram** to use |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Every VHDL file MUST contain exactly ONE entity and at least ONE architecture.** A configuration is optional in modern synthesis flows.

## 1.5 VHDL Libraries & Packages — The "Toolbox"

Before any code, we declare libraries. Think of them as **preloaded toolboxes** in your workshop.

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_ARITH.ALL;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_UNSIGNED.ALL;
```

| Library/Package | Provides |
|-----------------|----------|
| `IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164` | 9-value logic system (`std_logic`) |
| `IEEE.STD_LOGIC_ARITH` | Arithmetic on `std_logic_vector` |
| `IEEE.STD_LOGIC_UNSIGNED` | Treats vectors as **unsigned** numbers |
| `IEEE.STD_LOGIC_SIGNED` | Treats vectors as **signed** (2's complement) |
| `IEEE.NUMERIC_STD` | Modern preferred arithmetic package |

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner Trap:** Mixing `STD_LOGIC_ARITH` with `STD_LOGIC_UNSIGNED` in the same file is **redundant** and may cause **synthesis tool warnings**. Modern code should prefer **`NUMERIC_STD`** exclusively.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# SECTION 2 — Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 VHDL Data Types — The Building Atoms

### 2.1.1 Scalar Types

| Type | Values | Use Case |
|------|--------|----------|
| `bit` | `'0'`, `'1'` | Pure 2-state simulation |
| `std_logic` | `'U','X','0','1','Z','W','L','H','-'` | **Industry standard** for synthesis |
| `boolean` | `TRUE`, `FALSE` | Conditions, loops |
| `integer` | Whole numbers | Counters, addresses |
| `natural` | Integers ≥ 0 | Loop bounds |
| `real` | Floating point | **Non-synthesizable** for most targets |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The 9-value `std_logic` system is crucial for KTU board exams.** Always memorize the meanings:
> - `'U'` = Uninitialized (startup)
> - `'X'` = Forcing Unknown (conflict)
> - `'Z'` = High-Impedance (tri-state buffer)
> - `'W'`, `'L'`, `'H'` = Weak variants (pull-up/down)
> - `'-'` = Don't Care (synthesis optimization hint)

### 2.1.2 Composite Types

- **`std_logic_vector(n downto 0)`** — Bit-vector; `downto` is **mandatory** for descending ranges in synthesis.
- **`bit_vector`** — Older 2-state version.
- **Arrays** — User-defined (rare in basic KTU scope).
- **Records** — Group of mixed-type signals (advanced).

## 2.2 Operators in VHDL (Operator Precedence Cheat Sheet)

Listed from **highest to lowest precedence**:

| Priority | Operator Class | Operators |
|----------|----------------|-----------|
| 1 (highest) | Miscellaneous | `**`, `abs`, `not` |
| 2 | Multiplying | `*`, `/`, `mod`, `rem` |
| 3 | Sign | `+`, `-` (unary) |
| 4 | Adding | `+`, `-` |
| 5 | Shift | `rol`, `ror`, `srl`, `sll`, `sra` |
| 6 | Relational | `=`, `/=`, `<`, `>`, `<=`, `>=` |
| 7 (lowest) | Logical | `and`, `or`, `nand`, `nor`, `xor`, `xnor` |

> [!CAUTION]
> **KTU Pitfall:** `and`, `or`, `nand`, `xor` are **logical** operators in VHDL — they work on `std_logic` directly. Do **NOT** use the bitwise `&` for concatenation in arithmetic contexts; reserve `&` for **bit concatenation only**.

## 2.3 Concurrent vs Sequential Statements — The Fundamental Split

This is **THE most important conceptual boundary** in VHDL:

| Property | Concurrent Statements | Sequential Statements |
|----------|----------------------|------------------------|
| **Location** | Direct in architecture | Inside a `process` |
| **Execution** | **All in parallel**, every time a signal changes | In **strict order**, top-to-bottom |
| **Hardware Equivalent** | Wires & logic gates | Registers, state machines |
| **Examples** | `when`, `with-select`, `generate`, concurrent `=` | `if-then-else`, `case`, `for-loop`, `wait`, `if` |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Exam Golden Rule:** A **`process`** is itself a **concurrent statement**, but **inside** the process, statements execute **sequentially**. Outside, every assignment line is concurrent and order-independent.

## 2.4 The `PROCESS` Statement — Sequential Engine Inside Concurrent World

A `process` has a **sensitivity list** — a set of signals that, when changed, **trigger** the process to re-evaluate.

```vhdl
process(sensitivity_list)
    -- variable declarations (optional)
begin
    -- sequential statements
end process;
```

**Rules:**
1. A process with a sensitivity list **cannot contain `wait`**.
2. A process **without** a sensitivity list **must** contain at least one `wait`.
3. Variables declared inside a process are **local** and reset on each invocation (like software locals).
4. Signals assigned inside a process take effect **only after** the process suspends (this is the **delta delay** concept).

## 2.5 Signal vs Variable — The Two-State Memory

| Feature | `signal` | `variable` |
|---------|----------|------------|
| Scope | Architecture-wide (global) | Process/Subprogram (local) |
| Update | After process suspends (**delta delay**) | **Immediately** (no delay) |
| Use | Wires, registers, inter-process | Loop counters, temporary computations |
| Keyword | `signal name : type := initial_value;` | `variable name : type := initial_value;` |

> [!WARNING]
> **This is THE most-asked VHDL viva question in KTU labs.** A student once lost **4 marks** for using `signal` where `variable` was needed inside a `for-loop`.

## 2.6 KTU Formula Sheet — Concurrency & Simulation Timing

| Formula/Concept | Expression | Meaning |
|-----------------|-----------|---------|
| **Delta Delay** | $\Delta t = \text{infinitesimally small}$ | Event scheduling time-step in simulation |
| **Event** | $E_s = \{\text{signal} \to \text{value}\}$ | A signal changing value |
| **Process Trigger** | $\forall s \in S_{\text{list}}: \Delta s \neq 0$ | Any sensitivity list signal changes |
| **Signal Update Equation** | $s_{\text{new}} = s_{\text{old}} + \Delta t \cdot \frac{\partial s}{\partial t}$ | Discrete update at next delta cycle |
| **Simulation Cycle** | Execute → Update → Repeat | Until stable state |
| **Concurrency Theorem** | $\text{Hardware} = \text{Concurrent execution of all statements}$ | All statements run "simultaneously" |

## 2.7 Real-World Engineering Utility

VHDL is the **industry backbone** for:
- **FPGA Design:** Xilinx (Vivado), Intel/Altera (Quartus), Lattice (Diamond).
- **ASIC Design Front-End:** Synopsys Design Compiler, Cadence Genus.
- **Aerospace & Defense:** DO-254 compliance (formal verification is VHDL/SystemVerilog).
- **Telecommunications:** 5G baseband, optical transport ASICs.
- **Automotive (ISO 26262):** ADAS, ECU design.
- **AI Accelerators:** Custom ASICs for ML inference.

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# SECTION 3 — Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Generic VHDL Code Skeleton (Derivation of Standard Form)

Every synthesizable VHDL file in KTU follows this **canonical structure**:

```vhdl
-- ============================================
-- Step 1: LIBRARY & PACKAGE DECLARATIONS
-- ============================================
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;
use IEEE.NUMERIC_STD.ALL;   -- modern preferred package

-- ============================================
-- Step 2: ENTITY DECLARATION (Interface)
-- ============================================
entity <entity_name> is
    port (
        a     : in  std_logic;
        b     : in  std_logic;
        clk   : in  std_logic;
        rst   : in  std_logic;
        y     : out std_logic;
        q     : out std_logic_vector(3 downto 0)
    );
end entity <entity_name>;

-- ============================================
-- Step 3: ARCHITECTURE BODY (Behavior/Structure)
-- ============================================
architecture <arch_name> of <entity_name> is
    -- Declarations (signal, constant, component)
begin
    -- Concurrent & sequential statements
end architecture <arch_name>;
```

## 3.2 Analytical Matrix — Three Description Styles

### 3.2.1 Style 1 — Dataflow (Concurrent `with-select`)

**Example: 4-to-1 Multiplexer (Data Flow)**

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity mux4x1_df is
    port ( a, b, c, d : in  std_logic;
           s           : in  std_logic_vector(1 downto 0);
           y           : out std_logic);
end entity mux4x1_df;

architecture dataflow of mux4x1_df is
begin
    with s select
        y <= a when "00",
             b when "01",
             c when "10",
             d when others;     -- "11" and any 'X','U' etc.
end architecture dataflow;
```

**Derivation of selection logic:**
The MUX boolean equation: $y = \overline{s_1}\overline{s_0}a + \overline{s_1}s_0 b + s_1\overline{s_0}c + s_1 s_0 d$.

For `when others` to be safe, it catches `'X'`, `'U'`, `'Z'` — **synthesis-friendly latches avoided**.

### 3.2.2 Style 2 — Behavioral (`process`)

**Example: 4-to-1 Multiplexer (Behavioral)**

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity mux4x1_bh is
    port ( a, b, c, d : in  std_logic;
           s           : in  std_logic_vector(1 downto 0);
           y           : out std_logic);
end entity mux4x1_bh;

architecture behavioral of mux4x1_bh is
begin
    process(a, b, c, d, s)
    begin
        case s is
            when "00" => y <= a;
            when "01" => y <= b;
            when "10" => y <= c;
            when others => y <= d;
        end case;
    end process;
end architecture behavioral;
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Examiner Insight:** Every option of `case` must be covered, or the **last must be `when others`** — otherwise, an **inferred latch** is created in hardware, which is a **synthesis warning + marks deduction**.

### 3.2.3 Style 3 — Structural (Component Instantiation)

**Example: Half Adder built from primitives**

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity half_adder_str is
    port ( x, y : in  std_logic;
           s, c  : out std_logic);
end entity half_adder_str;

architecture structural of half_adder_str is
    component AND2 port (a, b : in std_logic; q : out std_logic); end component;
    component OR2  port (a, b : in std_logic; q : out std_logic); end component;
    component XOR2 port (a, b : in std_logic; q : out std_logic); end component;
    signal t1, t2 : std_logic;
begin
    U1: XOR2 port map (x, y, t1);
    U2: AND2 port map (x, y, t2);
    U3: OR2  port map (t1, t2, c);  -- c = x XOR y  -- mistaken, s should be t1
end architecture structural;
```

> [!NOTE]
> The above is illustrative. For a real half-adder, `s <= x xor y`, `c <= x and y`. **Correction:** S should be `t1` (XOR result) and carry is `t2`.

## 3.3 Combinational Circuit Codes

### 3.3.1 Full Adder (Behavioral Style)

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity full_adder is
    port ( a, b, cin : in  std_logic;
           sum, cout : out std_logic);
end entity full_adder;

architecture beh of full_adder is
begin
    process(a, b, cin)
    begin
        sum  <= a xor b xor cin;
        cout <= (a and b) or (b and cin) or (a and cin);
    end process;
end architecture beh;
```

**Boolean Derivation (Recall):**

$$\text{sum} = A \oplus B \oplus C_{in}$$
$$C_{out} = AB + BC_{in} + AC_{in}$$

### 3.3.2 4-Bit Ripple Carry Adder (Structural)

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity ripple_adder_4 is
    port ( a, b : in  std_logic_vector(3 downto 0);
           cin  : in  std_logic;
           sum  : out std_logic_vector(3 downto 0);
           cout : out std_logic);
end entity ripple_adder_4;

architecture structural of ripple_adder_4 is
    component full_adder
        port ( a, b, cin : in  std_logic;
               sum, cout : out std_logic);
    end component;
    signal c : std_logic_vector(4 downto 0);
begin
    c(0) <= cin;
    FA0: full_adder port map (a(0), b(0), c(0), sum(0), c(1));
    FA1: full_adder port map (a(1), b(1), c(1), sum(1), c(2));
    FA2: full_adder port map (a(2), b(2), c(2), sum(2), c(3));
    FA3: full_adder port map (a(3), b(3), c(3), sum(3), c(4));
    cout <= c(4);
end architecture structural;
```

**Derivation of Carry Propagation Delay:**

$$T_{\text{prop}} = n \cdot t_{\text{FA}}$$

Where $n = 4$ and $t_{\text{FA}}$ is one full-adder delay. **For KTU:** clearly state the **linear delay growth** as a disadvantage of ripple carry.

### 3.3.3 3-to-8 Decoder

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity decoder_3to8 is
    port ( en : in  std_logic;
           a  : in  std_logic_vector(2 downto 0);
           y  : out std_logic_vector(7 downto 0));
end entity decoder_3to8;

architecture beh of decoder_3to8 is
begin
    process(en, a)
    begin
        if en = '1' then
            y <= "00000001" when a = "000" else
                 "00000010" when a = "001" else
                 "00000100" when a = "010" else
                 "00001000" when a = "011" else
                 "00010000" when a = "100" else
                 "00100000" when a = "101" else
                 "01000000" when a = "110" else
                 "10000000";
        else
            y <= (others => '0');
        end if;
    end process;
end architecture beh;
```

### 3.3.4 8-to-3 Priority Encoder

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity prio_enc_8to3 is
    port ( d   : in  std_logic_vector(7 downto 0);
           y   : out std_logic_vector(2 downto 0);
           vld : out std_logic);
end entity prio_enc_8to3 is;

architecture beh of prio_enc_8to3 is
begin
    process(d)
    begin
        if    d(7) = '1' then y <= "111";
        elsif d(6) = '1' then y <= "110";
        elsif d(5) = '1' then y <= "101";
        elsif d(4) = '1' then y <= "100";
        elsif d(3) = '1' then y <= "011";
        elsif d(2) = '1' then y <= "010";
        elsif d(1) = '1' then y <= "001";
        elsif d(0) = '1' then y <= "000";
        else                  y <= "XXX";
        end if;
        vld <= '1' when d /= "00000000" else '0';
    end process;
end architecture beh;
```

### 3.3.5 4-Bit Comparator

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;
use IEEE.NUMERIC_STD.ALL;

entity comp_4bit is
    port ( a, b : in  std_logic_vector(3 downto 0);
           agb, aeb, alb : out std_logic);
end entity comp_4bit;

architecture beh of comp_4bit is
begin
    process(a, b)
    begin
        if    a > b then agb <= '1'; aeb <= '0'; alb <= '0';
        elsif a = b then agb <= '0'; aeb <= '1'; alb <= '0';
        else            agb <= '0'; aeb <= '0'; alb <= '1';
        end if;
    end process;
end architecture beh;
```

## 3.4 Sequential Circuit Codes (Clocked)

### 3.4.1 D Flip-Flop with Asynchronous Reset

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity d_ff_async_rst is
    port ( d, clk, rst : in  std_logic;
           q, qb        : out std_logic);
end entity d_ff_async_rst;

architecture beh of d_ff_async_rst is
begin
    process(clk, rst)
    begin
        if rst = '1' then
            q  <= '0';
            qb <= '1';
        elsif rising_edge(clk) then
            q  <= d;
            qb <= not d;
        end if;
    end process;
end architecture beh;
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Concept Test:** *Why is `rst` in the sensitivity list?*
> **Answer:** Because it's **asynchronous** — it acts immediately, independent of clock edge. For **synchronous reset**, omit `rst` from sensitivity list and use only `rising_edge(clk)`.

### 3.4.2 T Flip-Flop

The boolean characteristic equation: $Q_{n+1} = T \oplus Q_n = T\overline{Q_n} + \overline{T}Q_n$

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity t_ff is
    port ( t, clk, rst : in  std_logic;
           q, qb        : out std_logic);
end entity t_ff;

architecture beh of t_ff is
    signal q_int : std_logic := '0';
begin
    process(clk, rst)
    begin
        if rst = '1' then
            q_int <= '0';
        elsif rising_edge(clk) then
            if t = '1' then
                q_int <= not q_int;
            end if;
        end if;
    end process;
    q  <= q_int;
    qb <= not q_int;
end architecture beh;
```

### 3.4.3 4-Bit Synchronous Up Counter

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;
use IEEE.NUMERIC_STD.ALL;

entity counter_up_4bit is
    port ( clk, rst, en : in  std_logic;
           q             : out std_logic_vector(3 downto 0));
end entity counter_up_4bit;

architecture beh of counter_up_4bit is
    signal count : unsigned(3 downto 0) := (others => '0');
begin
    process(clk)
    begin
        if rst = '1' then
            count <= (others => '0');
        elsif rising_edge(clk) then
            if en = '1' then
                count <= count + 1;
            end if;
        end if;
    end process;
    q <= std_logic_vector(count);
end architecture beh;
```

**Count Sequence Derivation:**

$$Q_{n+1} = Q_n + 1 \pmod{16}$$

| Cycle | Q (binary) | Decimal |
|-------|-----------|---------|
| 0 | 0000 | 0 |
| 1 | 0001 | 1 |
| ... | ... | ... |
| 15 | 1111 | 15 |
| 16 | 0000 (rollover) | 0 |

### 3.4.4 4-Bit Up/Down Counter with Direction Control

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;
use IEEE.NUMERIC_STD.ALL;

entity counter_updown is
    port ( clk, rst, up : in  std_logic;
           q              : out std_logic_vector(3 downto 0));
end entity counter_updown;

architecture beh of counter_updown is
    signal count : integer range 0 to 15 := 0;
begin
    process(clk)
    begin
        if rst = '1' then
            count <= 0;
        elsif rising_edge(clk) then
            if up = '1' then
                count <= count + 1;
            else
                count <= count - 1;
            end if;
        end if;
    end process;
    q <= std_logic_vector(to_unsigned(count, 4));
end architecture beh;
```

### 3.4.5 4-Bit Shift Register (Serial-In Serial-Out)

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity siso_shift_reg is
    port ( clk, rst, sin : in  std_logic;
           sout           : out std_logic);
end entity siso_shift_reg;

architecture beh of siso_shift_reg is
    signal reg : std_logic_vector(3 downto 0) := (others => '0');
begin
    process(clk, rst)
    begin
        if rst = '1' then
            reg <= (others => '0');
        elsif rising_edge(clk) then
            reg <= reg(2 downto 0) & sin;  -- shift right, MSB gets new bit
        end if;
    end process;
    sout <= reg(3);
end architecture beh;
```

### 3.4.6 Universal Shift Register (Parallel-In Parallel-Out)

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity usr_pipo is
    port ( clk, rst : in  std_logic;
           mode     : in  std_logic_vector(1 downto 0);
           sin_l, sin_r : in  std_logic;
           pin      : in  std_logic_vector(3 downto 0);
           pout     : out std_logic_vector(3 downto 0));
end entity usr_pipo;

architecture beh of usr_pipo is
    signal reg : std_logic_vector(3 downto 0) := (others => '0');
begin
    process(clk, rst)
    begin
        if rst = '1' then
            reg <= (others => '0');
        elsif rising_edge(clk) then
            case mode is
                when "00" => reg <= reg;                          -- Hold
                when "01" => reg <= reg(2 downto 0) & sin_l;      -- Shift Left
                when "10" => reg <= sin_r & reg(3 downto 1);      -- Shift Right
                when "11" => reg <= pin;                          -- Parallel Load
                when others => reg <= (others => '0');
            end case;
        end if;
    end process;
    pout <= reg;
end architecture beh;
```

### 3.4.7 Ring Counter (4-bit)

A ring counter circulates a single '1' through 4 flip-flops:

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity ring_counter_4 is
    port ( clk, rst : in  std_logic;
           q         : out std_logic_vector(3 downto 0));
end entity ring_counter_4;

architecture beh of ring_counter_4 is
    signal reg : std_logic_vector(3 downto 0) := "1000";
begin
    process(clk, rst)
    begin
        if rst = '1' then
            reg <= "1000";   -- initialize to start sequence
        elsif rising_edge(clk) then
            reg <= reg(2 downto 0) & reg(3);   -- circular shift right
        end if;
    end process;
    q <= reg;
end architecture beh;
```

**State Derivation:** Starting from `1000`, each clock shifts right:

| Cycle | State |
|-------|-------|
| 0 | 1000 |
| 1 | 0100 |
| 2 | 0010 |
| 3 | 0001 |
| 4 | 1000 (repeats) |

### 3.4.8 Johnson Counter (Twisted Ring)

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity johnson_counter is
    port ( clk, rst : in  std_logic;
           q         : out std_logic_vector(3 downto 0));
end entity johnson_counter;

architecture beh of johnson_counter is
    signal reg : std_logic_vector(3 downto 0) := "0000";
begin
    process(clk, rst)
    begin
        if rst = '1' then
            reg <= (others => '0');
        elsif rising_edge(clk) then
            reg <= reg(2 downto 0) & not reg(3);  -- inverted feedback
        end if;
    end process;
    q <= reg;
end architecture beh;
```

**Johnson Sequence Derivation:** For $n=4$ flip-flops, the counter has **8 unique states** (2n):

$$0 \to 8 \to 12 \to 14 \to 15 \to 7 \to 3 \to 1 \to 0 \text{ (modulus 8)}$$

$$\text{Modulus} = 2n = 2 \times 4 = 8$$

## 3.5 State Machine Codes (Mealy & Moore)

### 3.5.1 Mealy Machine — 101 Sequence Detector

**State Diagram:** Detect overlapping "101" pattern in a serial input stream.

**States:**
- `S0` (00): Initial / no useful bits seen
- `S1` (01): "1" seen
- `S2` (10): "10" seen
- Output `Z = 1` when in S2 AND input = 1 (Mealy: output depends on input)

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity mealy_101 is
    port ( clk, rst, x : in  std_logic;
           z            : out std_logic);
end entity mealy_101;

architecture beh of mealy_101 is
    type state_t is (S0, S1, S2);
    signal ps, ns : state_t;
begin
    -- State Register
    process(clk, rst)
    begin
        if rst = '1' then
            ps <= S0;
        elsif rising_edge(clk) then
            ps <= ns;
        end if;
    end process;
    -- Next State & Output Logic
    process(ps, x)
    begin
        case ps is
            when S0 =>
                if x = '1' then ns <= S1; else ns <= S0; end if;
                z <= '0';
            when S1 =>
                if x = '0' then ns <= S2; else ns <= S1; end if;
                z <= '0';
            when S2 =>
                if x = '1' then ns <= S1; z <= '1';
                else            ns <= S0; z <= '0';
                end if;
        end case;
    end process;
end architecture beh;
```

### 3.5.2 Moore Machine — 101 Sequence Detector

Moore: Output depends **only on present state**, so we need an extra state.

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;

entity moore_101 is
    port ( clk, rst, x : in  std_logic;
           z            : out std_logic);
end entity moore_101;

architecture beh of moore_101 is
    type state_t is (S0, S1, S2, S3);
    signal ps, ns : state_t;
begin
    process(clk, rst)
    begin
        if rst = '1' then ps <= S0;
        elsif rising_edge(clk) then ps <= ns;
        end if;
    end process;

    process(ps, x)
    begin
        case ps is
            when S0 => z <= '0';
                      if x = '1' then ns <= S1; else ns <= S0; end if;
            when S1 => z <= '0';
                      if x = '0' then ns <= S2; else ns <= S1; end if;
            when S2 => z <= '0';
                      if x = '1' then ns <= S3; else ns <= S0; end if;
            when S3 => z <= '1';
                      if x = '1' then ns <= S1; else ns <= S2; end if;
        end case;
    end process;
end architecture beh;
```

**Key Difference (KTU Exam Favourite):**

| Aspect | Mealy | Moore |
|--------|-------|-------|
| Output depends on | Present State + Input | Present State **only** |
| States needed | Fewer | More |
| Output timing | Can be **asynchronous** to clock | **Synchronized** to clock |

