## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!NOTE]
> **Quick Revision Checklist (Print This Before Exam):**

- ✅ **Entity = Interface**, **Architecture = Body** — Two mandatory units.
- ✅ Three description styles: **Behavioral** (process-based), **Dataflow** (concurrent), **Structural** (component-based).
- ✅ `std_logic` has **9 values** — memorise: `U`, `X`, `0`, `1`, `Z`, `W`, `L`, `H`, `-`.
- ✅ **Signal** updates with delta delay; **Variable** updates immediately.
- ✅ **`process(sensitivity_list)`** — all signals read inside must appear in the list.
- ✅ **Concurrent statements** = outside process; **Sequential** = inside process.
- ✅ Use `rising_edge(clk)` or `clk'event and clk='1'` for edge detection.
- ✅ **Asynchronous reset** = `rst` in sensitivity list; **Synchronous reset** = only inside `elsif rising_edge`.
- ✅ Avoid **latch inference** by covering all `case` branches with `when others`.
- ✅ **Mealy** output depends on state + input; **Moore** output depends on state only.
- ✅ **Ripple carry adder delay** = $n \cdot t_{FA}$ (linear in $n$).
- ✅ **Johnson counter** has modulus $2n$; **Ring counter** has modulus $n$.
- ✅ Use `library IEEE; use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL; use IEEE.NUMERIC_STD.ALL;` — the modern, synthesis-friendly preamble.
- ✅ `with-select` (dataflow) and `case` (behavioral) are equivalent for MUX/decoder coding.
- ✅ Component instantiation: `inst_label: component_name port map (port_list);` — positional or named association both valid.
- ✅ Always add **`when others`** to `case` statements for safety against unexpected `std_logic` values.
- ✅ Testbench code is for **simulation only** — never synthesize.
- ✅ FSM design: enumerate states → draw state diagram → write transition table → encode in VHDL.
- ✅ A 4-bit counter has **16 states** (modulus 16); a 3-bit counter has **8 states**.
- ✅ Overlapping sequence detection reuses partial matches (Mealy); non-overlapping resets state on detection.
- ✅ Shift register `reg <= reg(2 downto 0) & sin;` shifts right, MSB gets new bit.
- ✅ `to_unsigned(count, N)` converts integer to N-bit unsigned `std_logic_vector`.

